Polynomial Regression

Use the strongx data.

For strongx the forward and backward procedures pick the same d but it is possible these two methods would pick different d values.

Forward Regresion

library(faraway)
g1 = lm(crossx ~ energy, weights = sd^-2, strongx)
round(summary(g1)$coef,dig=3)
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)  148.473      8.079  18.378        0
## energy       530.835     47.550  11.164        0
g2 = lm(crossx ~ energy + I(energy^2), weights = sd^-2, strongx)
round(summary(g2)$coef,dig=3)
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)  183.830      6.459  28.461    0.000
## energy         0.971     85.369   0.011    0.991
## I(energy^2) 1597.505    250.587   6.375    0.000
g3 = lm(crossx ~ energy + I(energy^2) + I(energy^3) , weights = sd^-2, strongx)
round(summary(g3)$coef,dig=3) # Select d=2
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)   204.992     12.826  15.983    0.000
## energy       -472.866    268.862  -1.759    0.129
## I(energy^2)  4504.475   1600.789   2.814    0.031
## I(energy^3) -5220.597   2848.373  -1.833    0.117

Cubic term is not signifficant. In this case d=2.

Backward regression

After sequential elimination, process stops when d=2. Both methods lead to the same value of d.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
x=seq(0, 1, 0.01); out = poly(x, 3)
plot(range(x), range(out), type="n", xlab="x", ylab="") #orthogonal polynomials
for(i in 1:3) lines(x, out[,i], lty=i, col=i)
out = cbind(x, x^2, x^3);
plot(range(x), range(out), type="n",xlab="x", ylab="") #standard polynomials
for(i in 1:3) lines(x, out[,i], lty=i, col=i)

Lets look at predicted values:

library(faraway)
data(strongx)
attach(strongx)
g1 = lm(crossx ~ energy, weights = sd^-2, data=strongx)
g2 = lm(crossx ~ energy + I(energy^2), weights = sd^-2,data=strongx) 
g3 = lm(crossx ~ energy + I(energy^2) + I(energy^3), weights = sd^-2, data=strongx)
newx=data.frame(energy=seq(0.02, 0.4, 0.01));
plot(energy, crossx, xlab="energy", ylab="crossx")
lines(newx$energy, predict(g1, newx), col="black", lty=1);
lines(newx$energy,predict(g2, newx), col="blue", lty=2);
lines(newx$energy,predict(g3, newx), col="red", lty=1);

anova(g1,g2)
